<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,846,1136]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
A specimen previously identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar, 1906 sensu Baker" authorityYear="1927" box="[615,790,846,873]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Gergithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signatifrons">
<emphasis box="[615,790,846,873]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">G. signatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Baker C. F." box="[833,990,846,872]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="391 - 411" refId="ref9749" refString="Baker C. F. 1927. Spolia Mentawiensia: Homoptera-Fulgoroidea. Philippine Journal of Science 32: 391 - 411." type="journal article" year="1927">Baker (1927)</bibRefCitation>
from Siberut Island was examined (BMNH). It differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[514,565,884,910]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar, 1906 sensu Baker" authorityYear="1927" box="[714,886,884,910]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Gergithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signatifrons">
<emphasis box="[714,886,884,910]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">G. signatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 1) frons with wide blood-red longitudinal fascia medially and green fasciae laterally from upper margin to the line of antennae, lateral green fasciae curved inwards and connected by yellow transverse band, between it and clypeus also blood-red (the latter frons with red longitudinal fascia reaching metopoclypeal suture), lateral area pale yellowish, with black fascia near lateral margin below antennae; 2) clypeus blood-red medially, yellow laterally near metopoclypeal suture, and black-and-red below (the latter clypeus yellow medially and black laterally); 3) tegmen fulvous with straw yellow veins (the latter tegmen straw yellow).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,1177,1279]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
All of the above characteristics show Baker’s identified specimen to be distinct from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar, 1906 sensu Baker" authorityYear="1927" box="[1176,1350,1177,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Gergithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signatifrons">
<emphasis box="[1176,1350,1177,1203]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">G. signatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and probably a new species. As the specimen is a female we prefer to wait for males to become available in order to formally describe the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
